the hype around text-to-cad tools is everywhere rn, and i get it, it sounds cool to automate design/assembly. but honestly? most developers working on these tools are completely out of touch with how cad is actually used IRL

too often, devs are focused on flashy ai gimmicks no one in professional cad workflows needs, while ignoring the real pain points. they donâ€™t understand our workflows at all.

example: half the time, cad starts with a janky sketch only you can decipher and turning that mess into an accurate model is one of the first things ai should help with. imagine feeding it a few rough sketches and having it generate the optimal design based on key features you want to parametrize.

but whereâ€™s the input from people with years of design and manufacturing experience? without that, these tools are just blindfolded dart-throwing. we donâ€™t need another tool to make a 3D-printed toy or a raspberry pi case.

we need real solutions. for example:

example 1: i need help figuring out how to integrate a starter motor into a micro gas turbine I'm designing. but i donâ€™t want it in a position that screws with airflow through the turbine. the software should understand the engineering constraints I've already provided, then test different configurations and layouts while keeping key relations locked in place, and since it built my model in a smart way with easily controllable constraints it can iterate through quickly 

example 2: i need to implement methods from a research paper on dynamic kinematics and balancing into my design. the goal is to give my robot the ideal cg and balance so the motors arenâ€™t burning out just trying to keep it upright. the tool should take that paper as a baseline and apply it across all my component designs moving forward.

example 3: design my injection-molded enclosure to spec according to ASME y14.8. it needs "xyz" features, must be "xyz" thick, and will be made of "xyz" material. i want the tool to handle all of that automatically while staying compliant.

smart assembly features would be a great addition, like suggesting mates in a logical order or letting me type "metric fast-travel ultra-precision lead screws and nuts" and have it not only find those components but understand what i want to do with them. direct McMaster links would be a bonus.

to me the biggest gap is that these tools donâ€™t understand design intent. they should grasp what I'm working on and suggest relevant solutions. but a lot of that info is company IP or trade secrets no oneâ€™s sharing with some random ai tool.

what would be sick, though, is if it could watch me work on my design, figure out what I'm building, and recommend things in context, like suggesting off-the-shelf components instead of me reinventing the wheel.

part design is another mess. too many models look fine but fall apart the second you tweak something because theyâ€™re built on shaky foundations. a tool that checks and fixes design stability as you go? yes, please.

and donâ€™t even get me started on model trees.

like HONESTLY , if you  just give engineers a tool that takes the disaster of a tree half of us have , fixes all my sketches, and organizes everything cleanly, youâ€™d have most engineers sold on that alone.

